Overview¶

The project aims to classify facial expressions into seven categories[anger, disgust, neutral, happy, sad, suprise, and fear] using Pre-trained Keras Models, CNNs, SVMs, and ANNs.¶

Our goal is to build a model(s) that can accurately classify emotions

Diving deep into the project, I developed eight distinct models, bifurcating them based on their architecture and whether they incorporated class weights. Here's a breakdown:

Artificial Neural Network (ANN): One of the foundational architectures in deep learning. I built two versions: A standard ANN An ANN adjusted with class weights to counteract class imbalances Convolutional Neural Network (CNN): Given its prowess in handling image data, I leveraged CNNs for this task, resulting in: A conventional CNN A CNN enriched with class weights Support Vector Machine (SVM): A classical choice for classification, I crafted two SVM models: A vanilla SVM An SVM designed with class weights Pre-trained VGG16 Model: Leveraging transfer learning, I used the VGG16 architecture, pre-trained on the ImageNet dataset. I honed two variants: A standard VGG16 model A VGG16 model tailored with class weights Throughout the project, the idea of using class weights became integral. It ensured that the models weren't just focusing on the dominant classes but were also paying due attention to the minority ones, leading to a more holistic understanding of facial emotions.

In summary, this project encapsulated my venture into bridging the gap between human emotions and the digital realm. By harnessing the potential of these diverse model architectures, both weighted and unweighted, I aimed to create a robust and comprehensive facial emotion recognition system.

about the data set:

For the most part the data is already processed and sorted. The test and train directories(folders) both have 7 categories(anger, disgust, neutral, happy, sad, suprise, and fear). Each category has a folder of images within both directories so it has already been split into test and train. We will inspect the datasets and see if there is any processing such as scaling or normalization that needs to be done or if we can improve upon the dataset for modeling.

This project is based on a Kaggle dataset and previous competition. The dataset used is named fer2013.

The zip file is too large to add to my repository.

you can load it on kaggle using the following path commands:

def count_total_images(data_path):
    """
    Count the total number of images in a dataset directory.
    
    Parameters:
    data_path (str): The path to the dataset directory.
    
    Returns:
    int: The total number of images in the dataset.
    """
    total_images = 0
    for root, dirs, files in os.walk(data_path):
        total_images += len([file for file in files if file.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg'))])
    return total_images

total_train_images = count_total_images(train_data)
total_test_images = count_total_images(test_data)

    Parameters:

    Returns:
    dict: A dictionary with class names as keys and the number of samples as values.
    """
    class_distribution = {}
    for class_name in os.listdir(data_path):
        class_path = os.path.join(data_path, class_name)

    return class_distribution

Plotting the class distributions¶

In [31]:
def plot_class_distribution(class_distribution, title):
    """
    Plot the class distribution as a bar chart.
    
    Parameters:
    class_distribution (dict): A dictionary with class names as keys and the number of samples as values.
    title (str): The title of the plot.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.barplot(x=list(class_distribution.keys()), y=list(class_distribution.values()), palette='viridis')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Class')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Samples')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.show()

# Plot class distribution for training data
plot_class_distribution(train_class_distribution, 'Class Distribution in Training Data')

# Plot class distribution for testing data
plot_class_distribution(test_class_distribution, 'Class Distribution in Testing Data')

  • disgust class has the lowest number of samples in both training and testing datasets, with just 436 and 111 samples, respectively. This is significantly lower compared to other classes.

  • The happy class has the highest number of samples, with 7215 in the training dataset and 1774 in the testing dataset.

  • All other classes (angry, fear, neutral, sad, surprise) have a relatively more balanced distribution, although there are still noticeable differences in their sample counts.

Conclusion:¶

There is a class imbalance in the dataset, especially for the disgust class, which might lead to biased predictions in favor of classes with more samples, such as happy.

To address this class imbalance, we might consider the following strategy

Balanced Weights: Assign different weights to classes when training the model, with higher weights for minority classes.

def show_random_images(data_path, num_images=5):
    """
    Show random images from each class in the dataset.
    
    Parameters:
    data_path (str): The path to the dataset.
    num_images (int): Number of images to show from each class.
    """
    classes = os.listdir(data_path)
    for class_name in classes:
        class_path = os.path.join(data_path, class_name)
        if os.path.isdir(class_path):
            image_files = os.listdir(class_path)
            random_images = random.sample(image_files, num_images)
            
            plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
            plt.suptitle(class_name, fontsize=16)
            for i, image_file in enumerate(random_images):
                plt.subplot(1, num_images, i + 1)
                img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(class_path, image_file))
                img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
                plt.imshow(img)
                plt.axis('off')
            plt.show()

# Show random images from each class in the training dataset
show_random_images(train_data)

def check_image_sizes(data_path):
    """
    Check the sizes of images in the dataset and print unique sizes.
    
    Parameters:
    data_path (str): The path to the dataset.
    """
    sizes = set()
    for root, dirs, files in os.walk(data_path):
        for file in files:
            if file.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg')):
                img_path = os.path.join(root, file)
                img = cv2.imread(img_path)
                sizes.add(img.shape)
                
    print("Unique image sizes:", sizes)

# Check image sizes in the training dataset
check_image_sizes(train_data)

def plot_pixel_distribution(data_path):
    """
    Plot the distribution of pixel values in the dataset.
    
    Parameters:
    data_path (str): The path to the dataset.
    """
    pixel_values = []
    for root, dirs, files in os.walk(data_path):
        for file in files:
            if file.lower().endswith(('.png', '.jpg', '.jpeg')):
                img_path = os.path.join(root, file)
                img = cv2.imread(img_path, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)  # Assuming grayscale images
                pixel_values.extend(img.ravel())
                
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.hist(pixel_values, bins=255, color='gray', alpha=0.7)
    plt.title('Pixel Value Distribution')
    plt.xlabel('Pixel Value')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()

# Plot pixel value distribution for the training dataset

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout

def create_cnn_model(input_shape):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(7, activation='softmax'))
    return model

# Without class weights
model_without_weights = create_cnn_model((48, 48, 3))
model_without_weights.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
history_without_weights = model_without_weights.fit(train_generator, epochs=10, validation_data=validation_generator)

# With class weights
model_with_weights = create_cnn_model((48, 48, 3))
model_with_weights.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
history_with_weights = model_with_weights.fit(train_generator, epochs=10, validation_data=validation_generator, class_weight=class_weights)

import numpy as np
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# Preprocess the data
X_train, y_train = next(train_generator)
X_val, y_val = next(validation_generator)

# Flatten the data
X_train_flat = X_train.reshape(X_train.shape[0], -1)
X_val_flat = X_val.reshape(X_val.shape[0], -1)

# Convert one-hot encoded labels to single numbers
y_train_single = np.argmax(y_train, axis=1)
y_val_single = np.argmax(y_val, axis=1)

# Initialize SVM without class weights
svm_clf_without_weights = svm.SVC(kernel='linear')

# Train SVM without class weights
svm_clf_without_weights.fit(X_train_flat, y_train_single)

# Predictions and Evaluation for SVM without class weights
y_pred_svm_without_weights = svm_clf_without_weights.predict(X_val_flat)
print("Classification Report for SVM without Class Weights:")
print(classification_report(y_val_single, y_pred_svm_without_weights))

# Initialize SVM with class weights
svm_clf_with_weights = svm.SVC(class_weight=class_weights, kernel='linear')

# Train SVM with class weights
svm_clf_with_weights.fit(X_train_flat, y_train_single)

# Predictions and Evaluation for SVM with class weights
y_pred_svm_with_weights = svm_clf_with_weights.predict(X_val_flat)
print("Classification Report for SVM with Class Weights:")
print(classification_report(y_val_single, y_pred_svm_with_weights))

Pre-trained Keras Model "VGG16"¶

In [76]:
def create_vgg16_model(input_shape):
    base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=input_shape)
    x = Flatten()(base_model.output)
    x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
    predictions = Dense(7, activation='softmax')(x)
    model = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=predictions)
    return model

# Without class weights
vgg_model_without_weights = create_vgg16_model((48, 48, 3))
vgg_model_without_weights.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
history_vgg_without_weights = vgg_model_without_weights.fit(train_generator, epochs=10, validation_data=validation_generator)

# With class weights
vgg_model_with_weights = create_vgg16_model((48, 48, 3))

def plot_history(history, title=''):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    
    # Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title(f'Accuracy {title}')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Val'], loc='upper left')
    
    # Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.title(f'Loss {title}')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epoch')
    plt.legend(['Train', 'Val'], loc='upper left')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_confusion_matrix(model, generator):
    # Getting predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(generator)
    y_pred_classes = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)
    y_true = generator.classes
    
    # Confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred_classes, labels=labels)
    
    # Plotting
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.ylabel('True')
    plt.show()

Project Conclusion¶

The best performing model was the CNN model WITHOUT the weights. So it is interesting to see that computed the weights actually made the model perform worse. The worst performing model was the VGG16 model with weights. The VGG model took painstakingly long to train also. It took a little over two hours to train those two models. The other model types trained in a couple minutes or less. What I notice is the fact is, most of the notebooks that worked with this dataset did not use a validation set. I thought the training set was too big in comparison to the test data set not to create a validation set.The CNN model without weights has these stats[loss: 1.5293 - accuracy: 0.5203] It had the smallest loss and the highest accuracy. Relative to the other models this is actually decent performance. I was dissapointed by the performance of the Keras Pre-Trained Model. It did not perform nearly as well as I thought it would, It actually performed significantly worst in comparison to the other models. I hope I provided descriptive visualizations and created a thorough project.

Model Accuracy and Loss Comparison¶

Overview:¶

The bar chart displays a comparison of the accuracy of various machine learning models with and without weights.

Key Observations:¶

  • The CNN models (both with and without weights) have the highest accuracy.
  • The ANN and SVM models have lower accuracy compared to VGG16 and CNN models.
  • The addition of weights seems to make a difference in model performance for some models, while for others, it does not.

Detailed Breakdown:¶

1. ANN Model:¶

Without Weights:

  • Accuracy: Started around 0.28 and peaked at approximately 0.33 before slightly declining.
  • Loss: Started near 1.9 and gradually reduced to around 1.73.

With Weights:

  • Accuracy: Fluctuated between 0.05 and 0.25.
  • Loss: Remained relatively constant around 1.95-2.02 range.

2. VGG16 Model:¶

Without Weights:

  • Accuracy: Remained relatively constant, with minor fluctuations around 0.245 to 0.251.
  • Loss: Started near 1.824 and exhibited minor fluctuations ending around 1.815.

Recommendations:¶

  • For highest accuracy, consider using or further tuning the CNN model.
  • Investigate the data and model architectures further to determine the reasons behind the performance discrepancies and the impact of weights.
